# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sql-server
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sql-server/database-engine-tutorials] Access to this page requires authorization.
[src:sql-server/database-engine-tutorials] You can try signing in or changing directories.
[src:sql-server/database-engine-tutorials] This section contains tutorials for SQL Server Database Engine.
[src:sql-server/database-engine-tutorials] Tutorial: Getting Started with the Database Engine This tutorial teaches how to connect to an instance of the Database Engine.
[src:sql-server/database-engine-tutorials] Tutorial: SQL Server Management Studio This tutorial introduces you to the integrated environment for managing your SQL Server infrastructure.
[src:sql-server/database-engine-tutorials] SQL Server Management Studio presents a graphical interface for configuring, monitoring, and administering instances of SQL Server.
[src:sql-server/database-engine-tutorials] It also allows you to deploy, monitor, and upgrade the data-tier components used by your applications, such as databases and data warehouses.
[src:sql-server/database-engine-tutorials] SQL Server Management Studio also provides Transact-SQL, MDX, DMX, and XML language editors for editing and debugging scripts.
[src:sql-server/database-engine-tutorials] Tutorial: Writing Transact-SQL Statements This tutorial teaches the fundamental skills of writing the Transact-SQL statements for creating and managing objects in a SQL Server database.
[src:sql-server/database-engine-tutorials] Tutorial: Database Engine Tuning Advisor This tutorial introduces you to using the advisor to examine how queries are processed, and then review recommendations for improving query performance.
[src:sql-server/database-engine-tutorials] Tutorial: Using the hierarchyid Data Type This tutorial teaches how to convert a table to a hierarchical structure, and then manage the data in the table.
[src:sql-server/database-engine-tutorials] Tutorial: Signing Stored Procedures with a Certificate This tutorial illustrates signing stored procedures using a certificate generated by SQL Server.
[src:sql-server/database-engine-tutorials] Tutorial: Ownership Chains and Context Switching This tutorial uses a scenario to illustrate SQL Server security concepts involving ownership chains and user context switching.
[src:sql-server/database-engine-tutorials] Tutorial: Administering Servers by Using Policy-Based Management This tutorial teaches how to create policies that enforce site administration standards.
[src:sql-server/database-engine-tutorials] Tutorial: SQL Server Backup and Restore to Azure Blob Storage This tutorial illustrates how to do a SQL Server backup and restore to Azure Blob Storage.
[src:sql-server/database-engine-tutorials] Tutorial: Use Azure Blob Storage with SQL Server databases This tutorial helps you understand how to store SQL Server data files in Azure Blob Storage directly.
[src:sql-server/indexes-indexes] The following table lists the types of indexes available in SQL Server and provides links to additional information.
[src:sql-server/indexes-indexes] Documentation uses the term B-tree generally in reference to indexes.
[src:sql-server/indexes-indexes] In rowstore indexes, the Database Engine implements a B+ tree.
[src:sql-server/indexes-indexes] This does not apply to columnstore indexes or indexes on memory-optimized tables.
[src:sql-server/indexes-indexes] For more information, see the SQL Server and Azure SQL index architecture and design guide.
[src:sql-server/language-reference] This article gives the basics about how to find and use the Microsoft Transact-SQL (T-SQL) reference articles.
[src:sql-server/language-reference] T-SQL is central to using Microsoft SQL products and services.
[src:sql-server/language-reference] All tools and applications that communicate with a SQL Server database do so by sending T-SQL commands.
[src:sql-server/language-reference] For detailed technical documents about how certain standards are implemented in SQL Server, see the Microsoft SQL Server Standards Support documentation.
[src:sql-server/language-reference] To find T-SQL articles, use search at the top right of this page, or use the table of contents on the left side of the page.
[src:sql-server/language-reference] You can also type a T-SQL key word in the Management Studio Query Editor window, and press F1.
[src:sql-server/language-reference] For more information, see Transact-SQL statements.
[src:sql-server/language-reference] To find the system tables, views, functions, and procedures, see these links, which are in the Databases section of the SQL documentation.
[src:sql-server/language-reference] The T-SQL reference articles encompass multiple versions of SQL Server, starting with SQL Server 2008 (10.0.x), and the other Azure SQL services.
[src:sql-server/language-reference] Near the top of each article, is a section that indicates which products and services support subject of the article.
[src:sql-server/language-reference] For example, this article applies to all versions, and has the following label.
[src:sql-server/language-reference] Another example, the following label indicates an article that applies only to Azure Synapse Analytics and Parallel Data Warehouse.
[src:sql-server/language-reference] In some cases, the article is used by a product or service, but all of the arguments aren't supported.
[src:sql-server/language-reference] In this case, other **Applies to** sections are inserted into the appropriate argument descriptions in the body of the article.
[src:sql-server/language-reference] For more information, see SQL Server docs navigation guide.
[src:sql-server/language-reference] For online help, see the Microsoft Q & A Transact-SQL Forum.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] The history of Microsoft SQL Server begins with the first Microsoft SQL Server product—SQL Server 1.0, a 16-bit server for the OS/2 operating system in 1989—and extends to the current day.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Its name is entirely descriptive, it being *server* software that responds to queries in the *SQL* language.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] From SQL Server 2016 onward, the product is supported on x64 processors only and must have 1.4 GHz processor as a minimum, 2.0 GHz or faster is recommended.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] The current version is Microsoft SQL Server 2025, released November 18, 2025.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Microsoft makes SQL Server available in multiple editions, with different feature sets and targeting different users.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] SQL Server Enterprise Edition includes both the core database engine and add-on services, with a range of tools for creating and managing a SQL Server cluster.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] of memory and supports 640 logical processors (CPU cores).
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] SQL Server Standard edition includes the core database engine, along with the stand-alone services.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] It differs from Enterprise edition in that it supports fewer active instances (number of nodes in a cluster) and does not include some high-availability functions such as hot-add memory (allowing memory to be added while the server is still running), and parallel indexes.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Introduced in SQL Server 2012 and focusing on Self Service and Corporate Business Intelligence.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] , Power View, the BI Semantic Model, Master Data Services, Data Quality Services and xVelocity in-memory analytics.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] SQL Server Workgroup Edition includes the core database functionality but does not include the additional services.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Note that this edition has been retired in SQL Server 2012.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Edition is a scaled down, free edition of SQL Server, which includes the core database engine.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] GB database files prior to SQL Server Express 2008 R2).
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Two additional editions provide a superset of features not in the original Express Edition.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] adds full-text search capability and reporting services.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Unlike the other editions of SQL Server, the SQL CE engine is based on SQL Mobile (initially designed for use with hand-held devices) and does not share the same binaries.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] MB DLL footprint), it has a markedly reduced feature set compared to the other editions.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] For example, it supports a subset of the standard data types, does not support stored procedures or Views or multiple-statement batches (among other limitations).
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] GB maximum database size and cannot be run as a Windows service, Compact Edition must be hosted by the application using it.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] The 3.5 version includes support for ADO.NET Synchronization Services.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] SQL CE does not support ODBC connectivity, unlike SQL Server proper.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] SQL Server Developer Edition includes the same features as SQL Server Enterprise Edition, but is limited by the license to be only used as a development and test system, and not as production server.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Starting early 2016, Microsoft made this edition free of charge to the public.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Starting with SQL Server 2025, Developer Edition is available in Standard Developer Edition and Enterprise Developer Edition with the same features with Standard Edition and Enterprise Edition, respectively.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] is a specially configured named instance of the SQL Server Express database engine which can be accessed only by certain Windows Services.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] , has all the features of the Enterprise Edition, but is limited to 180 days, after which the tools will continue to run, but the server services will stop.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] SQL Server Fast Track is specifically for enterprise-scale data warehousing storage and business intelligence processing, and runs on reference-architecture hardware that is optimized for Fast Track.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Introduced in SQL Server Express 2012, LocalDB is a minimal, on-demand, version of SQL Server that is designed for application developers.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] It can also be used as an embedded database.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Pre-installed and configured as part of an appliance in partnership with Dell & HP base on the Fast Track architecture.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] This edition does not include SQL Server Integration Services, Analysis Services, or Reporting Services.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Version 1.0 is based on SQL Server version 7.0.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Afterwards, it was replaced by Microsoft SQL Server Data Engine.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Also called Desktop Engine, Desktop Edition, it is based on SQL Server 2000.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] , Microsoft development tools, and other editions of SQL Server.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Intended for use with those management and development tools, it did not include any other GUI.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Later, Microsoft also made available a web admin tool.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] After SQL Server 2000, it was replaced by SQL Server 2005 Express Edition.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Had workload or connection limits like MSDE, but no database size limit.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Intended for use as a mobile / disconnected proxy, licensed for use with SQL Server 2000 Standard edition.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Similar to Standard Edition in SQL Server 2000, but Full-Text Search not working in Windows 98, transactional replication limited to subscriber.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] SQL Server 2008 R2 Datacenter is a full-featured edition of SQL Server and is designed for datacenters that need high levels of application support and scalability.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] It supports 256 logical processors and virtually unlimited memory and comes with StreamInsight Premium edition.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] The Datacenter edition has been retired in SQL Server 2012; all of its features are available in SQL Server 2012 Enterprise Edition.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] and was replaced by SQL Server 2005 Mobile Edition.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Replaced by SQL Server 2005 Compact Edition after 1 release.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] The protocol layer implements the external interface to SQL Server.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] All operations that can be invoked on SQL Server are communicated to it via a Microsoft-defined format, called Tabular Data Stream (TDS).
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] TDS is an application layer protocol, used to transfer data between a database server and a client.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Initially designed and developed by Sybase Inc. for their Sybase SQL Server relational database engine in 1984, and later by Microsoft in Microsoft SQL Server, TDS packets can be encased in other physical transport dependent protocols, including TCP/IP, named pipes, and shared memory.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Consequently, access to SQL Server is available over these protocols.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] In addition, the SQL Server API is also exposed over web services.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Data storage is a database, which is a collection of tables with typed columns.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] SQL Server supports different data types, including primitive types such as *Integer*, *Float*, *Decimal*, *Char* (including character strings), *Varchar* (variable length character strings), binary (for unstructured blobs of data), *Text* (for textual data) among others.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] The rounding of floats to integers uses either Symmetric Arithmetic Rounding or Symmetric Round Down (*fix*) depending on arguments: `SELECT Round(2.5, 0)` gives 3.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Microsoft SQL Server also allows user-defined composite types (UDTs) to be defined and used.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] It also makes server statistics available as virtual tables and views (called Dynamic Management Views or DMVs).
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] In addition to tables, a database can also contain other objects including views, stored procedures, indexes and constraints, along with a transaction log.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] A SQL Server database can contain a maximum of 231 objects, and can span multiple OS-level files with a maximum file size of 260 bytes (1 exabyte).
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] The data in the database are stored in primary data files with an extension `.mdf`.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Secondary data files, identified with a `.ndf` extension, are used to allow the data of a single database to be spread across more than one file, and optionally across more than one file system.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Log files are identified with the `.ldf` extension.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Storage space allocated to a database is divided into sequentially numbered *pages*, each 8 KB in size.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] A *page* is the basic unit of I/O for SQL Server operations.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] A page is marked with a 96-byte header which stores metadata about the page including the page number, page type, free space on the page and the ID of the object that owns it.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] The page type defines the data contained in the page.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] While a page is the basic unit of an I/O operation, space is actually managed in terms of an *extent* which consists of 8 pages.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] A database object can either span all 8 pages in an extent ("uniform extent") or share an extent with up to 7 more objects ("mixed extent").
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] A row in a database table cannot span more than one page, so is limited to 8 KB in size.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] However, if the data exceeds 8 KB and the row contains *varchar* or *varbinary* data, the data in those columns are moved to a new page (or possibly a sequence of pages, called an *allocation unit*) and replaced with a pointer to the data.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] For physical storage of a table, its rows are divided into a series of partitions (numbered 1 to n).
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] The partition size is user defined; by default all rows are in a single partition.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] A table is split into multiple partitions in order to spread a database over a computer cluster.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Rows in each partition are stored in either B-tree or heap structure.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] If the table has an associated, clustered index to allow fast retrieval of rows, the rows are stored in-order according to their index values, with a B-tree providing the index.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] The data is in the leaf node of the leaves, and other nodes storing the index values for the leaf data reachable from the respective nodes.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] If the index is non-clustered, the rows are not sorted according to the index keys.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] An indexed view has the same storage structure as an indexed table.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] A table without a clustered index is stored in an unordered heap structure.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] However, the table may have non-clustered indices to allow fast retrieval of rows.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] In some situations the heap structure has performance advantages over the clustered structure.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Both heaps and B-trees can span multiple allocation units.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] SQL Server buffers pages in RAM to minimize disk I/O.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Any 8 KB page can be buffered in-memory, and the set of all pages currently buffered is called the buffer cache.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] The amount of memory available to SQL Server decides how many pages will be cached in memory.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] The buffer cache is managed by the *Buffer Manager*.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Either reading from or writing to any page copies it to the buffer cache.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Subsequent reads or writes are redirected to the in-memory copy, rather than the on-disc version.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] The page is updated on the disc by the Buffer Manager only if the in-memory cache has not been referenced for some time.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] While writing pages back to disc, asynchronous I/O is used whereby the I/O operation is done in a background thread so that other operations do not have to wait for the I/O operation to complete.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Each page is written along with its checksum when it is written.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] When reading the page back, its checksum is computed again and matched with the stored version to ensure the page has not been damaged or tampered with in the meantime.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] SQL Server allows multiple clients to use the same database concurrently.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] As such, it needs to control concurrent access to shared data, to ensure data integrity—when multiple clients update the same data, or clients attempt to read data that is in the process of being changed by another client.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] SQL Server provides two modes of concurrency control: pessimistic concurrency and optimistic concurrency.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] When pessimistic concurrency control is being used, SQL Server controls concurrent access by using locks.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Locks can be either shared or exclusive.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] An exclusive lock grants the user exclusive access to the data—no other user can access the data as long as the lock is held.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Shared locks are used when some data is being read—multiple users can read from data locked with a shared lock, but not acquire an exclusive lock.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] The latter would have to wait for all shared locks to be released.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Locks can be applied on different levels of granularity—on entire tables, pages, or even on a per-row basis on tables.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] For indexes, it can either be on the entire index or on index leaves.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] The level of granularity to be used is defined on a per-database basis by the database administrator.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] While a fine-grained locking system allows more users to use the table or index simultaneously, it requires more resources, so it does not automatically yield higher performance.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] SQL Server also includes two more lightweight mutual exclusion solutions—latches and spinlocks—which are less robust than locks but are less resource intensive.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] SQL Server uses them for DMVs and other resources that are usually not busy.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] SQL Server also monitors all worker threads that acquire locks to ensure that they do not end up in deadlocks—in case they do, SQL Server takes remedial measures, which in many cases are to kill one of the threads entangled in a deadlock and roll back the transaction it started.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] To implement locking, SQL Server contains the *Lock Manager*.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] The Lock Manager maintains an in-memory table that manages the database objects and locks, if any, on them along with other metadata about the lock.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Access to any shared object is mediated by the lock manager, which either grants access to the resource or blocks it.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] SQL Server also provides the optimistic concurrency control mechanism, which is similar to the multiversion concurrency control used in other databases.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] The mechanism allows a new version of a row to be created whenever the row is updated, as opposed to overwriting the row, i.e., a row is additionally identified by the ID of the transaction that created the version of the row.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Both the old as well as the new versions of the row are stored and maintained, though the old versions are moved out of the database into a system database identified as `Tempdb`.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] When a row is in the process of being updated, any other requests are not blocked (unlike locking) but are executed on the older version of the row.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] If the other request is an update statement, it will result in two different versions of the rows—both of them will be stored by the database, identified by their respective transaction IDs.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] The main mode of retrieving data from a SQL Server database is querying for it.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] The query is expressed using a variant of SQL called T-SQL, a dialect Microsoft SQL Server shares with Sybase SQL Server due to its legacy.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] The query declaratively specifies what is to be retrieved.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] It is processed by the query processor, which figures out the sequence of steps that will be necessary to retrieve the requested data.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] The sequence of actions necessary to execute a query is called a query plan.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] There might be multiple ways to process the same query.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] For example, for a query that contains a join statement and a select statement, executing join on both the tables and then executing select on the results would give the same result as selecting from each table and then executing the join, but result in different execution plans.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] In such case, SQL Server chooses the plan that is expected to yield the results in the shortest possible time.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] This is called query optimization and is performed by the query processor itself.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] SQL Server includes a cost-based query optimizer which tries to optimize on the cost, in terms of the resources it will take to execute the query.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Given a query, then the query optimizer looks at the database schema, the database statistics and the system load at that time.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] It then decides which sequence to access the tables referred in the query, which sequence to execute the operations and what access method to be used to access the tables.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] For example, if the table has an associated index, whether the index should be used or not: if the index is on a column which is not unique for most of the columns (low "selectivity"), it might not be worthwhile to use the index to access the data.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Finally, it decides whether to execute the query concurrently or not.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] While a concurrent execution is more costly in terms of total processor time, because the execution is actually split to different processors might mean it will execute faster.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Once a query plan is generated for a query, it is temporarily cached.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] For further invocations of the same query, the cached plan is used.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Unused plans are discarded after some time.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] SQL Server also allows stored procedures to be defined.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Stored procedures are parameterized T-SQL queries, that are stored in the server itself (and not issued by the client application as is the case with general queries).
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Stored procedures can accept values sent by the client as input parameters, and send back results as output parameters.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] They can call defined functions, and other stored procedures, including the same stored procedure (up to a set number of times).
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] They can be selectively provided access to.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Unlike other queries, stored procedures have an associated name, which is used at runtime to resolve into the actual queries.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Also because the code need not be sent from the client every time (as it can be accessed by name), it reduces network traffic and somewhat improves performance.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Execution plans for stored procedures are also cached as necessary.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] T-SQL (Transact-SQL) is Microsoft's proprietary procedural language extension for SQL Server.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] It provides REPL (Read-Eval-Print-Loop) instructions that extend standard SQL's instruction set for Data Manipulation (DML) and Data Definition (DDL) instructions, including SQL Server-specific settings, security and database statistics management.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] It exposes keywords for the operations that can be performed on SQL Server, including creating and altering database schemas, entering and editing data in the database as well as monitoring and managing the server itself.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Client applications that consume data or manage the server will leverage SQL Server functionality by sending T-SQL queries and statements which are then processed by the server and results (or errors) returned to the client application.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] For this it exposes read-only tables from which server statistics can be read.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Management functionality is exposed via system-defined stored procedures which can be invoked from T-SQL queries to perform the management operation.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] It is also possible to create linked Servers using T-SQL.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Linked servers allow a single query to process operations performed on multiple servers.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] SQL Server Native Client is the native client side data access library for Microsoft SQL Server, version 2005 onwards.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] SQL Server Native Client is used under the hood by SQL Server plug-ins for other data access technologies, including ADO or OLE DB.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] The SQL Server Native Client can also be directly used, bypassing the generic data access layers.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] On November 28, 2011, a preview release of the SQL Server ODBC driver for Linux was released.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Microsoft SQL Server 2005 includes a component named SQL CLR ("Common Language Runtime") via which it integrates with .NET Framework.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Unlike most other applications that use .NET Framework, SQL Server itself hosts the .NET Framework runtime, i.e., memory, threading and resource management requirements of .NET Framework are satisfied by SQLOS itself, rather than the underlying Windows operating system.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] SQLOS provides deadlock detection and resolution services for .NET code as well.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] With SQL CLR, stored procedures and triggers can be written in any managed .NET language, including C# and VB.NET.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Managed code can also be used to define UDT's (user defined types), which can persist in the database.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Managed code is compiled to CLI assemblies and after being verified for type safety, registered at the database.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] After that, they can be invoked like any other procedure.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] However, only a subset of the Base Class Library is available, when running code under SQL CLR.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Most APIs relating to user interface functionality are not available.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] When writing code for SQL CLR, data stored in SQL Server databases can be accessed using the ADO.NET APIs like any other managed application that accesses SQL Server data.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] However, doing that creates a new database session, different from the one in which the code is executing.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] To avoid this, SQL Server provides some enhancements to the ADO.NET provider that allows the connection to be redirected to the same session which already hosts the running code.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Such connections are called context connections and are set by setting `context connection` parameter to `true` in the connection string.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] SQL Server also provides several other enhancements to the ADO.NET API, including classes to work with tabular data or a single row of data as well as classes to work with internal metadata about the data stored in the database.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] It also provides access to the XML features in SQL Server, including XQuery support.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] These enhancements are also available in T-SQL Procedures in consequence of the introduction of the new XML Datatype (query, value, nodes functions).
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] SQL Server also includes an assortment of add-on services.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] While these are not essential for the operation of the database system, they provide value added services on top of the core database management system.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] These services either run as a part of some SQL Server component or out-of-process as Windows Service and presents their own API to control and interact with them.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] SQL Server Agent is a component of Microsoft SQL Server which schedules jobs and handles other automated tasks.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] It runs as a Windows service so it can start automatically when the system boots or it can be started manually.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Typical system tasks performed include scheduling maintenance plans (such as backups), handling Reporting Services subscriptions and performing log shipping sub-tasks (backup, copy, restore & check).
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] User tasks, such as scheduling some T-SQL or command line statement are also common.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] SQLAgent has support for operators and alerts, so that administrators can be notified, e.g. by email.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] The SQL Server Machine Learning services operates within the SQL server instance, allowing people to do machine learning and data analytics without having to send data across the network or be limited by the memory of their own computers.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] The services come with Microsoft's R and Python distributions that contain commonly used packages for data science, along with some proprietary packages (e.g. revoscalepy, RevoScaleR, microsoftml) that can be used to create machine models at scale.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Analysts can either configure their client machine to connect to a remote SQL server and push the script executions to it, or they can run a R or Python scripts as an external script inside a T-SQL query.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] The trained machine learning model can be stored inside a database and used for scoring.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Used inside an instance, programming environment.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] For cross-instance applications, Service Broker communicates over TCP/IP and allows the different components to be synchronized, via exchange of messages.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] The Service Broker, which runs as a part of the database engine, provides a reliable messaging and message queuing platform for SQL Server applications.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] The message type defines the data format used for the message.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] This can be an XML object, plain text or binary data, as well as a null message body for notifications.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] The contract defines which messages are used in an conversation between services and who can put messages in the queue.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] The queue acts as storage provider for the messages.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] They are internally implemented as tables by SQL Server, but do not support insert, update, or delete functionality.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] The service program receives and processes service broker messages.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Usually the service program is implemented as stored procedure or CLR application.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Routes are network addresses where the service broker is located on the network.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Also, service broker supports security features like network authentication (using NTLM, Kerberos, or authorization certificates), integrity checking, and message encryption.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] SQL Server Replication Services are used by SQL Server to replicate and synchronize database objects, either in entirety or a subset of the objects present, across replication agents, which might be other database servers across the network, or database caches on the client side.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Replication Services follows a publisher/subscriber model, i.e., the changes are sent out by one database server ("publisher") and are received by others ("subscribers").
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Each transaction made to the publisher database (master database) is synced out to subscribers, who update their databases with the transaction.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Transactional replication synchronizes databases in near real time.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Changes made at both the publisher and subscriber databases are tracked, and periodically the changes are synchronized bi-directionally between the publisher and the subscribers.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] If the same data has been modified differently in both the publisher and the subscriber databases, synchronization will result in a conflict which has to be resolved, either manually or by using pre-defined policies.Rowguid needs to be configured on a column if merge replication is configured.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Snapshot replication publishes a copy of the entire database (the then-snapshot of the data) and replicates out to the subscribers.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Further changes to the snapshot are not tracked.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] SQL Server Analysis Services (SSAS) adds OLAP and data mining capabilities for SQL Server databases.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] The OLAP engine supports MOLAP, ROLAP and HOLAP storage modes for data.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Analysis Services supports the XML for Analysis standard as the underlying communication protocol.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] The cube data can be accessed using MDX and LINQ queries.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Data mining specific functionality is exposed via the DMX query language.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Analysis Services includes various algorithms—Decision trees, clustering algorithm, Naive Bayes algorithm, time series analysis, sequence clustering algorithm, linear and logistic regression analysis, and neural networks—for use in data mining.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] SQL Server Reporting Services (SSRS) is a report generation environment for data gathered from SQL Server databases.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Reporting services features a web services interface to support the development of custom reporting applications.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Reports can be designed using recent versions of Microsoft Visual Studio (Visual Studio.NET 2003, 2005, and 2008) with Business Intelligence Development Studio, installed or with the included Report Builder.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Once created, RDL files can be rendered in a variety of formats, including Excel, PDF, CSV, XML, BMP, EMF, GIF, JPEG, PNG, and TIFF, and HTML Web Archive.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Originally introduced as a post-release add-on for SQL Server 2000, Notification Services was bundled as part of the Microsoft SQL Server platform for the first and only time with SQL Server 2005.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] SQL Server Notification Services is a mechanism for generating data-driven notifications, which are sent to Notification Services subscribers.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] A subscriber registers for a specific event or transaction (which is registered on the database server as a trigger); when the event occurs, Notification Services can use one of three methods to send a message to the subscriber informing about the occurrence of the event.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] These methods include SMTP, SOAP, or by writing to a file in the filesystem.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Notification Services was discontinued by Microsoft with the release of SQL Server 2008 in August 2008, and is no longer an officially supported component of the SQL Server database platform.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] SQL Server Integration Services (SSIS) provides ETL capabilities for SQL Server for data import, data integration and data warehousing needs.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Integration Services includes GUI tools to build workflows such as extracting data from various sources, querying data, transforming data—including aggregation, de-duplication, de-/normalization and merging of data—and then exporting the transformed data into destination databases or files.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] SQL Server Full Text Search service is a specialized indexing and querying service for unstructured text stored in SQL Server databases.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] The full text search index can be created on any column with character based text data.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] It allows for words to be searched for in the text columns.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] While it can be performed with the SQL `LIKE` operator, using SQL Server Full Text Search service can be more efficient.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Full allows for inexact matching of the source string, indicated by a *Rank* value which can range from 0 to 1000—a higher rank means a more accurate match.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] It also allows linguistic matching ("inflectional search"), i.e., linguistic variants of a word (such as a verb in a different tense) will also be a match for a given word (but with a lower rank than an exact match).
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Proximity searches are also supported, i.e., if the words searched for do not occur in the sequence they are specified in the query but are near each other, they are also considered a match.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] T-SQL exposes special operators that can be used to access the FTS capabilities.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] The Full Text Search engine is divided into two processes: the *Filter Daemon* process (`msftefd.exe`) and the *Search* process (`msftesql.exe`).
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] These processes interact with the SQL Server.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] The Search process includes the indexer (that creates the full text indexes) and the full text query processor.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] The indexer scans through text columns in the database.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] It can also index through binary columns, and use iFilters to extract meaningful text from the binary blob (for example, when a Microsoft Word document is stored as an unstructured binary file in a database).
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] The iFilters are hosted by the Filter Daemon process.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Once the text is extracted, the Filter Daemon process breaks it up into a sequence of words and hands it over to the indexer.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] The indexer filters out *noise words*, i.e., words like *A*, *And*, etc., which occur frequently and are not useful for search.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] With the remaining words, an inverted index is created, associating each word with the columns they were found in.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] SQL Server itself includes a *Gatherer* component that monitors changes to tables and invokes the indexer in case of updates.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] When a full text query is received by the SQL Server query processor, it is handed over to the FTS query processor in the Search process.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] The FTS query processor breaks up the query into the constituent words, filters out the noise words, and uses an inbuilt thesaurus to find out the linguistic variants for each word.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] The words are then queried against the inverted index and a rank of their accurateness is computed.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] The results are returned to the client via the SQL Server process.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] SQLCMD is a command line application that comes with Microsoft SQL Server, and exposes the management features of SQL Server.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] It allows SQL queries to be written and executed from the command prompt.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] It can also act as a scripting language to create and run a set of SQL statements as a script.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Such scripts are stored as a `.sql` file, and are used either for management of databases or to create the database schema during the deployment of a database.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] SQLCMD was introduced with SQL Server 2005 and has continued through SQL Server versions 2008, 2008 R2, 2012, 2014, 2016 and 2019.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Its predecessor for earlier versions was OSQL and ISQL, which were functionally equivalent as it pertains to T-SQL execution, and many of the command line parameters are identical, although SQLCMD adds extra versatility.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Microsoft Visual Studio includes native support for data programming with Microsoft SQL Server.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] It can be used to write and debug code to be executed by SQL CLR.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] It also includes a *data designer* that can be used to graphically create, view or edit database schemas.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Queries can be created either visually or using code.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] SSMS 2008 onwards, provides intellisense for SQL queries as well.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] SQL Server Management Studio is a GUI tool included with SQL Server 2005 and later for configuring, managing, and administering all components within Microsoft SQL Server.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] The tool includes both script editors and graphical tools that work with objects and features of the server.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] SQL Server Management Studio replaces Enterprise Manager as the primary management interface for Microsoft SQL Server since SQL Server 2005.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] A version of SQL Server Management Studio is also available for SQL Server Express Edition, for which it is known as *SQL Server Management Studio Express* (SSMSE).
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] A central feature of SQL Server Management Studio is the Object Explorer, which allows the user to browse, select, and act upon any of the objects within the server.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] It can be used to visually observe and analyze query plans and optimize the database performance, among others.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] SQL Server Management Studio can also be used to create a new database, alter any existing database schema by adding or modifying tables and indexes, or analyze performance.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] It includes the query windows which provide a GUI based interface to write and execute queries.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Azure Data Studio is a cross platform query editor available as an optional download.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] The tool allows users to write queries; export query results; commit SQL scripts to Git repositories and perform basic server diagnostics.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Azure Data Studio runs on Windows, Mac and Linux systems and is retiring on February 28 2026.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] It was released to General Availability in September 2018.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Prior to release the preview version of the application was known as SQL Server Operations Studio.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] Business Intelligence Development Studio (BIDS) is the IDE from Microsoft used for developing data analysis and Business Intelligence solutions utilizing the Microsoft SQL Server Analysis Services, Reporting Services and Integration Services.
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] It is based on the Microsoft Visual Studio development environment but is customized with the SQL Server services-specific extensions and project types, including tools, controls and projects for reports (using Reporting Services), Cubes and data mining structures (using Analysis Services).
[src:sql-server/microsoft-sql-server] For SQL Server 2012 and later, this IDE has been renamed SQL Server Data Tools (SSDT).
[src:sql-server/sql-server-management-studio] A central feature of SSMS is the Object Explorer, which allows the user to browse, select, and act upon any of the objects within the server.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-management-studio] It also shipped a separate Express edition that could be freely downloaded; however recent versions of SSMS are fully capable of connecting to and manage any SQL Server Express instance.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-management-studio] Microsoft also incorporated backwards compatibility for older versions of SQL Server thus allowing a newer version of SSMS to connect to older versions of SQL Server instances.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-management-studio] It also comes with Microsoft SQL Server Express 2012, or users can download it separately.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-management-studio] Starting from version 11, the application was based on the Visual Studio 2010 shell, using WPF for the user interface.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-management-studio] Versions 18 and after are based on the Visual Studio 2017 Isolated Shell.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-management-studio] In June 2015, Microsoft announced their intention to release future versions of SSMS independently of SQL Server database engine releases.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-management-studio] Since version 21 SSMS is based on Visual Studio 2022 and is installed using the Visual Studio Installer.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Every SQL Server database has a transaction log that records all transactions and the database modifications that are made by each transaction.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] The transaction log is a critical component of the database and, if there's a system failure, the transaction log might be required to bring your database back to a consistent state.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] This guide provides information about the physical and logical architecture of the transaction log.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Understanding the architecture can improve your effectiveness in managing transaction logs.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] The SQL Server transaction log operates logically as if the transaction log is a string of log records.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Each log record is identified by a *log sequence number* (LSN).
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Each new log record is written to the logical end of the log with an LSN that is higher than the LSN of the record before it.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Log records are stored in a serial sequence as they're created, such that if LSN2 is greater than LSN1, the change described by the log record referred to by LSN2 occurred after the change described by the log record LSN1.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Each log record contains the ID of the transaction that it belongs to.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] For each transaction, all log records associated with the transaction are individually linked in a chain using backward pointers that speed the rollback of the transaction.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] The basic structure of an LSN is `[VLF ID:Log Block ID:Log Record ID]`.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] For more information, see the VLF and log block sections.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Here's an example of an LSN: `00000031:00000da0:0001`, where `0x31` is the ID of the VLF, `0xda0` is the log block ID, and `0x1` is the first log record in that log block.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] For examples of LSNs, look at the output of sys.dm_db_log_info DMV and examine the `vlf_create_lsn` column.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Log records for data modifications record either the logical operation performed, or they record the before and after images of the modified data.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] The *before image* is a copy of the data before the operation is performed; the *after image* is a copy of the data after the operation has been performed.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Many types of operations are recorded in the transaction log.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Each transaction reserves space in the transaction log to make sure that enough log space exists to support a rollback that is caused by either an explicit rollback statement, or if an error is encountered.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] The amount of space reserved depends on the operations performed in the transaction, but generally it's equal to the amount of space used to log each operation.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] This reserved space is freed when the transaction is completed.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] The section of the log file from the first log record that must be present for a successful database-wide rollback to the last-written log record is called the active part of the log, *active log*, or *tail of the log*.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] This is the section of the log required to a full recovery of the database.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] No part of the active log can ever be truncated.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] The log sequence number (LSN) of this first log record is known as the *minimum recovery LSN* (MinLSN).
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] For more information on operations supported by the transaction log, see The transaction log.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Differential and log backups advance the restored database to a later time, which corresponds to a higher LSN.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] The database transaction log maps over one or more physical files.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Conceptually, the log file is a string of log records.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Physically, the sequence of log records is stored efficiently in the set of physical files that implement the transaction log.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] There must be at least one log file for each database.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] The SQL Server Database Engine divides each physical log file internally into several virtual log files (VLFs).
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Virtual log files have no fixed size, and there's no fixed number of virtual log files for a physical log file.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] The Database Engine chooses the size of the virtual log files dynamically while it's creating or extending log files.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] The Database Engine tries to maintain a few virtual files.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] The size of the virtual files after a log file has been extended is the sum of the size of the existing log and the size of the new file increment.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] The size or number of virtual log files can't be configured or set by administrators.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] If the log files grow to a large size in many small increments, they end up with many virtual log files.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] **This can slow down database startup, log backup and restore operations, and cause transactional replication/CDC and Always On redo latency.** Conversely, if the log files are set to a large size with few or just one increment, they contain few very large virtual log files.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] For more information on properly estimating the **required size** and **autogrow** setting of a transaction log, see the *Recommendations* section of Manage the size of the transaction log file.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] We recommend that you create your log files close to the final size required, using the increments needed to achieve optimal VLF distribution, and have a relatively large *growth_increment* value.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] For more information on `FILEGROWTH` and `SIZE` arguments of `ALTER DATABASE`, see ALTER DATABASE (Transact-SQL) File and Filegroup Options.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] To determine the optimal VLF distribution for the current transaction log size of all databases in a given instance, and the required growth increments to achieve the required size, see this Fixing-VLFs script on GitHub.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] During the initial stages of a database recovery process, SQL Server discovers all VLFs in all transaction log files, and builds a list of these VLFs.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] This process can take a long time depending on the number of VLFs present in the specific database.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] A database can end up with large number of VLFs if frequent transaction log autogrowth or manual growth is encountered in small increments.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] When you examine the SQL Server Error log, you might notice that a significant amount of time is spent before the *analysis* phase of the database recovery process.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] For more information, see MSSQLSERVER_9017.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] After you set the new layout of the transaction log file with fewer VLFs, review and make necessary changes to the autogrow settings of the transaction log.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] This setting validation ensures that the log file avoids encountering the same problem in the future.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Before you perform any of these operations, make sure that you have a valid restorable backup in case you encounter issues later.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] To determine the optimal VLF distribution for the current transaction log size of all databases in a given instance, and the required growth increments to achieve the required size, you can use the following GitHub script to fix VLFs.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Each VLF contains one or more *log blocks*.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Each log block consists of the log records (aligned at a 4-byte boundary).
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] A log block is variable in size and is always an integer multiple of 512 bytes (the minimum sector size SQL Server supports), with a maximum size of 60 KB.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] A log block is the basic unit of I/O for transaction logging.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] In summary, a log block is a container of log records that's used as the basic unit of transaction logging when writing log records to disk.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Each log block within a VLF is uniquely addressed by its *block offset*.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] The first block always has a block offset that points past the first 8 KB in the VLF.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] In general, a VLF is always filled up with log blocks.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] It's possible that the last log block in a VLF is empty (for example, doesn't contain any log records).
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] This happens when a log record to be written doesn't fit into the current log block and also when the space left on the VLF is insufficient to hold this log record.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] In this case, an empty log block is created that fills up the VLF.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] The log record is inserted into the first block on the next VLF.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] The transaction log is a wrap-around file.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] For example, consider a database with one physical log file divided into four VLFs.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] When the database is created, the logical log file begins at the start of the physical log file.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] New log records are added at the end of the logical log and expand toward the end of the physical log.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Log truncation frees any virtual logs whose records all appear in front of the minimum recovery log sequence number (MinLSN).
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] The *MinLSN* is the log sequence number of the oldest log record that is required for a successful database-wide rollback.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] The transaction log in the example database would look similar to the one in the following diagram.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] When the end of the logical log reaches the end of the physical log file, the new log records wrap around to the start of the physical log file.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] This cycle repeats endlessly, as long as the end of the logical log never reaches the beginning of the logical log.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] If the old log records are truncated frequently enough to always leave sufficient room for all the new log records created through the next checkpoint, the log never fills.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] If the log contains multiple physical log files, the logical log moves through all the physical log files before it wraps back to the start of the first physical log file.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] For more information about transaction log size management, see Manage the size of the transaction log file.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Log truncation is essential to keep the log from filling.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Log truncation deletes inactive virtual log files from the logical transaction log of a SQL Server database, freeing space in the logical log for reuse by the physical transaction log.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] If a transaction log is never truncated, it will eventually fill all the disk space that is allocated to its physical log files.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] However, before the log can be truncated, a checkpoint operation must occur.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] A checkpoint writes the current in-memory modified pages (known as *dirty pages*) and transaction log information from memory to disk.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] When the checkpoint is performed, the inactive portion of the transaction log is marked as reusable.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Thereafter, a log truncation can free the inactive portion.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] For more information about checkpoints, see Database checkpoints (SQL Server).
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] The following diagrams show a transaction log before and after truncation.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] The first diagram shows a transaction log that has never been truncated.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Currently, four virtual log files are in use by the logical log.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] The logical log starts at the front of the first virtual log file and ends at virtual log 4.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Virtual log 1 and virtual log 2 contain only inactive log records.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Virtual log 5 is still unused and isn't part of the current logical log.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] The second diagram shows how the log appears after being truncated.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Virtual log 1 and virtual log 2 have been freed for reuse.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] The logical log now starts at the beginning of virtual log 3.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Virtual log 5 is still unused, and it isn't part of the current logical log.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Log truncation can be delayed by various factors.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] In the event of a long delay in log truncation, the transaction log can fill up.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] For information, see Factors that can delay log truncation and Troubleshoot a full transaction log (SQL Server Error 9002).
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] This section describes the role of the write-ahead transaction log in recording data modifications to disk.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] SQL Server uses a write-ahead logging (WAL) algorithm, which guarantees that no data modifications are written to disk before the associated log record is written to disk.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] This maintains the ACID properties for a transaction.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] For more information about WAL, see SQL Server I/O fundamentals.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] To understand how write-ahead logging works in relation to the transaction log, it's important for you to know how modified data is written to disk.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] SQL Server maintains a buffer cache (also called a buffer pool) into which it reads data pages when data must be retrieved.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] When a page is modified in the buffer cache, it isn't immediately written back to disk; instead, the page is marked as *dirty*.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] A data page can have more than one logical write made before it's physically written to disk.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] For each logical write, a transaction log record is inserted in the log cache that records the modification.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] The log records must be written to disk before the associated dirty page is removed from the buffer cache and written to disk.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] The checkpoint process periodically scans the buffer cache for buffers with pages from a specified database and writes all dirty pages to disk.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Checkpoints save time during a later recovery by creating a point at which all dirty pages are guaranteed to have been written to disk.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Writing a modified data page from the buffer cache to disk is called flushing the page.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] SQL Server has logic that prevents a dirty page from being flushed before the associated log record is written.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Log records are written to disk when the log buffers are flushed.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] This happens whenever a transaction commits or the log buffers become full.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] This section presents concepts about how to back up and restore (apply) transaction logs.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Under the full and bulk-logged recovery models, taking routine backups of transaction logs (*log backups*) is necessary for recovering data.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] You can back up the log while any full backup is running.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] For more information about recovery models, see Back up and restore of SQL Server databases.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Before you can create the first log backup, you must create a full backup, such as a database backup or the first in a set of file backups.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Restoring a database by using only file backups can become complex.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Therefore, we recommend that you start with a full database backup when you can.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Thereafter, backing up the transaction log regularly is necessary.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] This not only minimizes work-loss exposure but also enables truncation of the transaction log.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Typically, the transaction log is truncated after every conventional log backup.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] To limit the number of log backups that you need to restore, it's essential to routinely back up your data.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] For example, you might schedule a weekly full database backup and daily differential database backups.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Think about the required RTO and RPO when implementing your recovery strategy, and specifically the full and differential database backup cadence.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] For more information about transaction log backups, see Transaction log backups (SQL Server).
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] You should take frequent enough log backups to support your business requirements, specifically your tolerance for work loss such as might be caused by a damaged log storage.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] The appropriate frequency for taking log backups depends on your tolerance for work-loss exposure balanced by how many log backups you can store, manage, and, potentially, restore.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Think about the required recovery time objective (RTO) and recovery point objective (RPO) when implementing your recovery strategy, and specifically the log backup cadence.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Taking a log backup every 15 to 30 minutes might be enough.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] If your business requires that you minimize work-loss exposure, consider taking log backups more frequently.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] More frequent log backups have the added advantage of increasing the frequency of log truncation, resulting in smaller log files.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] A continuous sequence of log backups is called a *log chain*.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] A log chain starts with a full backup of the database.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Usually, a new log chain is only started when the database is backed up for the first time, or after the recovery model is switched from simple recovery to full or bulk-logged recovery.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Unless you choose to overwrite existing backup sets when creating a full database backup, the existing log chain remains intact.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] With the log chain intact, you can restore your database from any full database backup in the media set, followed by all subsequent log backups up through your recovery point.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] The recovery point could be the end of the last log backup or a specific recovery point in any of the log backups.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] For more information, see Transaction log backups (SQL Server).
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] To restore a database up to the point of failure, the log chain must be intact.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] That is, an unbroken sequence of transaction log backups must extend up to the point of failure.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Where this sequence of log must start depends on the type of data backups you're restoring: database, partial, or file.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] For a database or partial backup, the sequence of log backups must extend from the end of a database or partial backup.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] For a set of file backups, the sequence of log backups must extend from the start of a full set of file backups.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] For more information, see Apply Transaction Log Backups (SQL Server).
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Restoring a log backup rolls forward the changes that were recorded in the transaction log to recreate the exact state of the database at the time the log backup operation started.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] When you restore a database, you'll have to restore the log backups that were created after the full database backup that you restore, or from the start of the first file backup that you restore.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Typically, after you restore the most recent data or differential backup, you must restore a series of log backups until you reach your recovery point.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] This rolls back all transactions that were incomplete when the recovery started and brings the database online.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] After the database has been recovered, you can't restore any more backups.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Checkpoints flush dirty data pages from the buffer cache of the current database to disk.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] This minimizes the active portion of the log that must be processed during a full recovery of a database.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] The SQL Server Database Engine generates automatic checkpoints.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] The interval between automatic checkpoints is based on the amount of log space used and the time elapsed since the last checkpoint.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] The time interval between automatic checkpoints can be highly variable and long, if few modifications are made in the database.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Automatic checkpoints can also occur frequently if lots of data is modified.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Use the **recovery interval** server configuration option to calculate the interval between automatic checkpoints for all the databases on a server instance.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] This option specifies the maximum time the Database Engine should use to recover a database during a system restart.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] The Database Engine estimates how many log records it can process in the **recovery interval** during a recovery operation.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] For information about setting the recovery interval, see Server configuration: recovery interval (min).
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] The `-k` SQL Server advanced setup option enables a database administrator to throttle checkpoint I/O behavior based on the throughput of the I/O subsystem for some types of checkpoints.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] The `-k` setup option applies to automatic checkpoints and any otherwise unthrottled checkpoints.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Automatic checkpoints truncate the unused section of the transaction log if the database is using the simple recovery model.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] However, if the database is using the full or bulk-logged recovery models, the log isn't truncated by automatic checkpoints.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] For more information, see The transaction log.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] The `CHECKPOINT` statement now provides an optional checkpoint_duration argument that specifies the requested period of time, in seconds, for checkpoints to finish.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] The section of the log file from the MinLSN to the last-written log record is called the active portion of the log, or the active log.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] This is the section of the log required to do a full recovery of the database.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] All log records must be truncated from the parts of the log before the MinLSN.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] The following diagram shows a simplified version of the end-of-a-transaction log with two active transactions.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Checkpoint records have been compacted to a single record.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] LSN 148 is the last record in the transaction log.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] At the time that the recorded checkpoint at LSN 147 was processed, Tran 1 had been committed and Tran 2 was the only active transaction.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] That makes the first log record for Tran 2 the oldest log record for a transaction active at the time of the last checkpoint.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] This makes LSN 142, the Begin transaction record for Tran 2, the MinLSN.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] The active log must include every part of all uncommitted transactions.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] An application that starts a transaction and doesn't commit it or roll it back prevents the Database Engine from advancing the MinLSN.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] Recovery of long-running transactions, and the problems described in this article, can be avoided by using Accelerated database recovery, a feature available starting with SQL Server 2019 (15.x) and in Azure SQL Database.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] The Log Reader Agent monitors the transaction log of each database configured for transactional replication, and it copies the transactions marked for replication from the transaction log into the distribution database.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] The active log must contain all transactions that are marked for replication, but that haven't yet been delivered to the distribution database.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] If these transactions aren't replicated in a timely manner, they can prevent the truncation of the log.
[src:sql-server/sql-server-transaction-log-architecture-and-management-guide] For more information, see Transactional Replication.
[src:sql-server/stored-procedure] A **stored procedure** (also termed **prc**, **proc**, **storp**, **sproc**, **StoPro**, **StoredProc**, **StoreProc**, **sp**, or **SP**) is a subroutine available to applications that access a relational database management system (RDBMS).
[src:sql-server/stored-procedure] Such procedures are stored in the database data dictionary.
[src:sql-server/stored-procedure] Uses for stored procedures include data-validation (integrated into the database) or access-control mechanisms.
[src:sql-server/stored-procedure] Furthermore, stored procedures can consolidate and centralize logic that was originally implemented in applications.
[src:sql-server/stored-procedure] To save time and memory, extensive or complex processing that requires execution of several SQL statements can be saved into stored procedures, and all applications call the procedures.
[src:sql-server/stored-procedure] One can use nested stored procedures by executing one stored procedure from within another.
[src:sql-server/stored-procedure] Stored procedures may return result sets, i.e., the results of a `SELECT` statement.
[src:sql-server/stored-procedure] Such result sets can be processed using cursors, by other stored procedures, by associating a result-set locator, or by applications.
[src:sql-server/stored-procedure] Stored procedures may also contain declared variables for processing data and cursors that allow it to loop through multiple rows in a table.
[src:sql-server/stored-procedure] Stored-procedure flow-control statements typically include `IF`, `WHILE`, `LOOP`, `REPEAT`, and `CASE` statements, and more.
[src:sql-server/stored-procedure] Stored procedures can receive variables, return results or modify variables and return them, depending on how and where the variable is declared.
[src:sql-server/stored-procedure] Stored procedures are similar to user-defined functions (UDFs).
[src:sql-server/stored-procedure] The major difference is that UDFs can be used like any other expression within SQL statements, whereas stored procedures must be invoked using the `CALL` statement.
[src:sql-server/stored-procedure] The exact and correct implementation of stored procedures varies from one database system to the other.
[src:sql-server/stored-procedure] Most major database vendors support them in some form.
[src:sql-server/stored-procedure] Depending on the database system, stored procedures can be implemented in a variety of programming languages, for example SQL, Java, C, or C++.
[src:sql-server/stored-procedure] Stored procedures written in non-SQL languages may or may not execute SQL statements themselves.
[src:sql-server/stored-procedure] The increasing adoption of stored procedures led to the introduction of procedural elements to the SQL language in the SQL:1999 and SQL:2003 standards in the part SQL/PSM.
[src:sql-server/stored-procedure] That made SQL an imperative programming language.
[src:sql-server/stored-procedure] Most database systems offer proprietary and vendor-specific extensions, exceeding SQL/PSM.
[src:sql-server/stored-procedure] A standard specification for Java stored procedures exists as well as SQL/JRT.
[src:sql-server/stored-procedure] remove all or part of the compiling overhead that is typically needed when software applications send inline (dynamic) SQL queries to a database.
[src:sql-server/stored-procedure] and other methods to avoid repetitively compiling dynamic SQL statements.) Also, while they avoid some pre-compiled SQL, statements add to the complexity of creating an optimal execution plan because not all arguments of the SQL statement are supplied at compile time.
[src:sql-server/stored-procedure] Depending on the specific database implementation and configuration, mixed performance results will be seen from stored procedures versus generic queries or user defined functions.
[src:sql-server/stored-procedure] In a production system, this typically means that the procedures run entirely on a specialized database server with direct access to the data.
[src:sql-server/stored-procedure] The benefit is that it saves network costs, which stands out when a series of SQL statements are involved.
[src:sql-server/stored-procedure] as an API in the database, which can simplify data management and reduce the need to encode the logic elsewhere in client programs.
[src:sql-server/stored-procedure] This can result in a lesser likelihood of data corruption by faulty client programs.
[src:sql-server/stored-procedure] In many systems, stored procedures can be granted access rights to the database that users who execute those procedures do not directly have.
[src:sql-server/stored-procedure] Stored procedures can be used to protect against injection attacks.
[src:sql-server/stored-procedure] Stored procedure parameters will be treated as data even if an attacker inserts SQL commands.
[src:sql-server/stored-procedure] Also, some DBMS will check the parameter's type.
[src:sql-server/stored-procedure] However, a stored procedure that in turn generates dynamic SQL using the input is still vulnerable to SQL injections unless proper precautions are taken.
[src:sql-server/stored-procedure] In some systems, stored procedures can be used to control transaction management; in others, stored procedures run inside a transaction such that transactions are effectively transparent to them.
[src:sql-server/stored-procedure] Stored procedures can also be invoked from a database trigger or a condition handler.
[src:sql-server/stored-procedure] For example, a stored procedure may be triggered by an insert on a specific table, or update of a specific field in a table, and the code inside the stored procedure would be executed.
[src:sql-server/stored-procedure] Writing stored procedures as condition handlers also allows database administrators to track errors in the system with greater detail by using stored procedures to catch the errors and record some audit information in the database or an external resource like a file.
[src:sql-server/stored-procedure] Prepared statements take an ordinary statement or query and parameterize it so that different literal values can be used at a later time.
[src:sql-server/stored-procedure] Like stored procedures, they are stored on the server for efficiency and provide some protection from SQL injection attacks.
[src:sql-server/stored-procedure] Although simpler and more declarative, prepared statements are not ordinarily written to use procedural logic and cannot operate on variables.
[src:sql-server/stored-procedure] Because of their simple interface and client-side implementations, prepared statements are more widely reusable between DBMS.
[src:sql-server/stored-procedure] Smart contract is a term applied to executable code stored on a blockchain as opposed to an RDBMS.
[src:sql-server/stored-procedure] Despite the execution result consensus mechanisms of public blockchain networks differing in principle from traditional private or federated databases, they perform ostensibly the same function as stored procedures, albeit usually with a sense of value transaction.
[src:sql-server/transact-sql] Transact-SQL is central to using Microsoft SQL Server.
[src:sql-server/transact-sql] All applications that communicate with an instance of SQL Server do so by sending Transact-SQL statements to the server, regardless of the user interface of the application.
[src:sql-server/transact-sql] Stored procedures in SQL Server are executable server-side routines.
[src:sql-server/transact-sql] The advantage of stored procedures is the ability to pass parameters.
[src:sql-server/transact-sql] Transact-SQL provides the following statements to declare and set local variables: `DECLARE`, `SET` and `SELECT`.
[src:sql-server/transact-sql] Keywords for flow control in Transact-SQL include `BEGIN` and `END`, `BREAK`, `CONTINUE`, `GOTO`, `IF` and `ELSE`, `RETURN`, `WAITFOR`, and `WHILE`.
[src:sql-server/transact-sql] `IF` and `ELSE` allow conditional execution.
[src:sql-server/transact-sql] This batch statement will print "It is the weekend" if the current date is a weekend day, or "It is a weekday" if the current date is a weekday.
[src:sql-server/transact-sql] `BEGIN` and `END` mark a block of statements.
[src:sql-server/transact-sql] `WAITFOR` will wait for a given amount of time, or until a particular time of day.
[src:sql-server/transact-sql] The statement can be used for delays or to block execution until the set time.
[src:sql-server/transact-sql] `RETURN` is used to immediately return from a stored procedure or function.
[src:sql-server/transact-sql] `BREAK` ends the enclosing `WHILE` loop, while `CONTINUE` causes the next iteration of the loop to execute.
[src:sql-server/transact-sql] An example of a `WHILE` loop is given below.
[src:sql-server/transact-sql] This example deletes all `users` who have been flagged in the `user_flags` table with the 'idle' flag.
[src:sql-server/transact-sql] `BULK` is a Transact-SQL statement that implements a bulk data-loading process, inserting multiple rows into a table, reading data from an external sequential file.
[src:sql-server/transact-sql] Use of `BULK INSERT` results in better performance than processes that issue individual `INSERT` statements for each row to be added.
[src:sql-server/transact-sql] Additional details are available in MSDN.
[src:sql-server/transact-sql] Beginning with SQL Server 2005, Microsoft introduced additional `TRY CATCH` logic to support exception type behaviour.
[src:sql-server/transact-sql] This behaviour enables developers to simplify their code and leave out `@@ERROR` checking after each SQL execution statement.
